      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Indifferent to a Planet in Pain'' (Op-Ed, Sept. 4) underscores the importance of environmental issues in the 2000 Presidential campaign. As Bill McKibben notes, the Clinton Administration ''watched with little apparent concern'' as global-warming ''emissions surged more than 10 percent'' over the last decade.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Indifferent to a Planet in Pain'' (Op-Ed, Sept. 4) underscores the importance of environmental issues in the 2000 Presidential campaign. As Bill McKibben notes, the Clinton Administration ''watched with little apparent concern'' as global-warming ''emissions surged more than 10 percent'' over the last decade.</p>
        <p>The American people deserve to know what Al Gore, the ostensibly environmentally concerned Vice President, and the Republican and third-party candidates are planning to do to reverse this unfolding global catastrophe. The failure of developed countries and of the United States  in particular to address this issue forcefully and to abolish the destructive dominance of fossil fuels is the appalling legacy we may leave our children.</p>
        <p>GABE KIRCHHEIMER  New York, Sept. 4, 1999</p>
      </block>
